moves.3. Nf3 Bc5 4. Bc4 d6 5. Ng5 O-O 6. O-O N: Out of the database again.  Frriedel appears to favor this knight/bishop pawn/rook trade.
At this point black has three pawns out, white has three pawns out, but white also has a knight and bishop in the field and the king out.  Without queens the king becomes a much more potent piece, though black still has two rooks against white's one.
moves.14... c6 15. Be3 b5 16. Bb3 a5 17. a3 a4: At first blush this looks like a bad move, but PxB leaves Nf6 undefended.  This is actually a pretty decent move.
moves.20... Nh5+ 21. Kg4 Nf6+ 22. Kg5: Too hasty?  Kf5 seems like a better move.
This does not protect against NxPd6.
moves.36. c3: NxPd6 kind of forces Rh7 or Rf8, or Kf6, leaving the white knight free for more mischief.
moves.36... Nf4 37. Nxd6: There we go.  Pf7 looks like a goner.
moves.37... Rf8: I like NxPf7+, forcing Kf6 followed by NxPh6.
moves.38. d4: This splits white's beautiful and precious a-e string of pawns.
moves.38... exd4 39. cxd4: I still prefer NxPf7+.  The bishop is guarding it.  Kf6 results in KxNf4.
moves.39... Nd3: Now white loses Pb2.  NxPf7+ still picks up Ph6 too.
